var definitions = ['<h2>Você estava dormindo quando cheguei.</h2><div><strong>Você</strong> This is the Portuguese pronoun for "you" in a formal or informal context. It is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>estava</strong> This is the imperfect tense of the verb "estar", which means "to be" in English. It is used to describe a continuous state in the past.</div><div><strong>dormindo</strong> This is the gerund form of the verb "dormir", meaning "sleeping". In English, gerunds can often be identified by the -ing ending. In Portuguese, it combines with "estar" to describe the action of sleeping that was happening continuously or repeatedly in the past.</div><div><strong>quando</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "when". It introduces a time clause and indicates that the action of the main clause was occurring at the time of the action in the time clause.</div><div><strong>cheguei</strong> This is the first-person singular past tense (preterite) of the verb "chegar", meaning "I arrived". It tells us when the speaker arrived relative to the other person’s action of sleeping.</div>','<h2>Você fica linda quando sorri.</h2><div><strong>Você</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>fica</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "ficar", which means "to become" or "to stay" in this context. It is used here to describe a transformation or state of being.</div><div><strong>linda</strong> This is a Portuguese adjective meaning "beautiful". It agrees in gender and number with the subject "você" which is considered feminine in this context. If referring to a male subject, it would be "lindo".</div><div><strong>quando</strong> This word translates to "when" in English. It’s a conjunction used to introduce dependent clauses.</div><div><strong>sorri</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sorrir", which means "to smile". It aligns with the subject "você", showing the action performed by the subject.</div>','<h2>Me ligue quando você chegar em casa.</h2><div><strong>Me</strong> This is a clitic pronoun in Portuguese used here as the indirect object, meaning "to me". It indicates the person who should receive the call.</div><div><strong>ligue</strong> This is the third-person singular imperative of the verb "ligar", meaning "call". It’s used to give a command or request in this sentence.</div><div><strong>quando</strong> This is a conjunction that means "when". It’s used to introduce a subordinate clause indicating the timing of the action.</div><div><strong>você</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>chegar</strong> This is the third-person singular subjunctive of the verb "chegar", meaning "to arrive". It’s used in the subordinate clause to express an action that is anticipated or contingent upon something else.</div><div><strong>em casa</strong> This phrase means "at home". "em" is a preposition meaning "in" or "at", and "casa" is a noun meaning "home". Together, they indicate the location associated with the action of arriving.</div>','<h2>As crianças se divertem quando estão no parquinho.</h2><div><strong>As</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese for feminine plural nouns, equivalent to "the" in English. It precedes the noun "crianças".</div><div><strong>crianças</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "children". It is a feminine plural noun.</div><div><strong>se</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun used in conjunction with the verb "divertem". It indicates that the action of the verb is being performed by the subject onto themselves. In this context, it forms part of the reflexive verb "se divertir", which means "to have fun".</div><div><strong>divertem</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense form of the reflexive verb "divertir-se", which means "to have fun". It relates to "crianças", indicating that the children are the ones having fun.</div><div><strong>quando</strong> This is a conjunction that means "when" in English. It introduces a temporal clause that gives information about the time of the action.</div><div><strong>estão</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense of the verb "estar", which means "to be" in English. It describes the state of being of the subject "crianças" within the clause.</div><div><strong>no</strong> This is the contraction of the preposition "em" (in) and the definite article "o" (the), resulting in "no", which means "on the" or "in the" when referring to a masculine singular noun in English. Here it relates to "parquinho".</div><div><strong>parquinho</strong> This is a diminutive form of the Portuguese word "parque", which means "park". "Parquinho" implies a small park or a playground, which is a common place for children to have fun.</div>','<h2>Eles vão à piscina quando está calor.</h2><div><strong>Eles</strong> This is the third-person plural pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "they" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>vão</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense form of the verb "ir", which means "to go". Here, it indicates the action that the subject is taking.</div><div><strong>à</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "a" (to) with the definite article "a" (the), used here to indicate direction or destination. In English, it’s similar to "to the".</div><div><strong>piscina</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "pool". It is the destination where "they" are going when the condition of "when it is hot" is met.</div><div><strong>quando</strong> This word translates to "when" in English. It’s a conjunction used to introduce a dependent clause describing the time at which the action of the main clause takes place.</div><div><strong>está</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "estar", which means "to be". Here, it is used to describe a state of being, specifically, the weather condition.</div><div><strong>calor</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "heat". In this sentence, it describes the weather condition that triggers the action of going to the pool.</div>','<h2>Acredito que o tigre esteja furioso.</h2><div><strong>Acredito</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "acreditar", which means "to believe" in Portuguese. It’s used here to express the speaker’s belief.</div><div><strong>que</strong> This is a conjunction in Portuguese that means "that". It is used to introduce a subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>o</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese for masculine singular nouns, equivalent to "the" in English.</div><div><strong>tigre</strong> This is a masculine singular noun in Portuguese, which translates to "tiger" in English.</div><div><strong>esteja</strong> This word comes from the verb "estar", which means "to be" in Portuguese. It’s in the third-person singular present subjunctive form and is used to express uncertainty, possibility, or a state of being that is not definitive.</div><div><strong>furioso</strong> This is a Portuguese adjective meaning "angry" or "furious". It is agreeing in gender and number with the masculine singular noun "tigre".</div>','<h2>Espero que você esteja com fome!</h2><div><strong>Espero</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "esperar", which means "to hope" or "to expect" in English. It indicates the subject’s desire or expectation for something to occur.</div><div><strong>que</strong> This is a conjunction in Portuguese that often introduces a subordinate clause. In English, it translates to "that" in this context.</div><div><strong>você</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It is the subject of the subordinate clause. </div><div><strong>esteja</strong> This is the third-person singular present subjunctive tense of the verb "estar", which means "to be" in English. It expresses a state or condition that is uncertain or desired by the speaker.</div><div><strong>com</strong> This Portuguese preposition translates to "with" in English.</div><div><strong>fome</strong> This is a noun in Portuguese meaning "hunger". When combined with the preposition "com", the phrase "com fome" translates to "hungry" in English.</div>','<h2>É importante que você entenda.</h2><div><strong>É</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "ser", which means "to be" in Portuguese. It states the existence or a characteristic of something or someone.</div><div><strong>importante</strong> This is a Portuguese adjective meaning "important". It describes something that has significance or value. In this sentence, it modifies the clause that follows, suggesting the importance of the action described.</div><div><strong>que</strong> This word functions as a conjunction in Portuguese, often used to introduce subordinate clauses. In this sentence, it connects the main clause to the dependent clause that expresses what is important.</div><div><strong>você</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the subordinate clause being introduced by "que".</div><div><strong>entenda</strong> This is the second-person singular present subjunctive form of the verb "entender", which means "to understand" in Portuguese. The subjunctive mood is used to express doubts, wishes, or hypothetical situations. Here it is expressing the importance of the subject’s understanding of whatever matter is at hand.</div>','<h2>Disseram-me que você estava em casa.</h2><div><strong>Disseram-me</strong> This phrase comes from the verb "dizer" in Portuguese, which means "to tell". "Disseram" is the third-person plural form in the past tense, so it translates to "they told". The pronoun "me" attached to "Disseram" indicates that the speaker was told something, making the meaning "they told me".</div><div><strong>que</strong> This is a conjunction in Portuguese, which translates to "that" in English. It is used here to introduce a subordinate clause expressing what was told to the speaker.</div><div><strong>você</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English.</div><div><strong>estava</strong> This is the past tense of the verb "estar" in Portuguese, which means "to be". It describes the state of being of "você" in the past, so it translates to "were" in English.</div><div><strong>em casa</strong> This means "at home" in English. "Em" translates to "at" and "casa" means "home".</div>','<h2>Sei que você mentiu para mim.</h2><div><strong>Sei</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the Portuguese verb "saber", which means "to know". It indicates that the speaker is certain about what follows.</div><div><strong>que</strong> This is a conjunction in Portuguese that means "that". It is used to introduce a subordinate clause and connect it to the main clause ("sei").</div><div><strong>você</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s used as the subject of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>mentiu</strong> This is the third-person singular simple past tense form of the verb "mentir", which means "to lie". It indicates that the action of lying has occurred in the past.</div><div><strong>para</strong> This is a preposition in Portuguese that means "to" or "for". It indicates direction or recipients in various contexts, in this case, it’s used before "mim" to specify who was lied to.</div><div><strong>mim</strong> This is a personal pronoun in Portuguese that means "me". It is an object pronoun, indicating the person affected by the verb "mentiu" (lied).</div>','<h2>Que estudante!</h2><div><strong>Que</strong> This is the Portuguese word used to express an exclamation equivalent to "What a" in English. It highlights the quality, quantity, or nature of something or someone.</div><div><strong>estudante</strong> This is the Portuguese noun for "student". It can refer to a person who is studying in a school, college, or university. The word can be used for both masculine and feminine forms and does not change in its written form.</div>','<h2>Que artista importante!</h2><div><strong>Que</strong> This is a Portuguese word typically meaning "what" or "how". In this sentence, it’s being used as an exclamatory word, equivalent to "What an" in English.</div><div><strong>artista</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "artist". It’s a common gender noun and can refer to any person engaged in an activity related to creating art, practicing the arts, or demonstrating an art.</div><div><strong>importante</strong> This is the Portuguese adjective for "important". It’s being used here to describe the artist, indicating significance or prominence.</div>'];var defBonus = ['<h2>Ele será bombeiro quando crescer.</h2><div><strong>Ele</strong> Is the subject pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "he" in English. It represents the person who is the subject of the action in the sentence.</div><div><strong>será</strong> This is the future tense of the verb "ser" in Portuguese, meaning "to be". It indicates an action or state that will occur in the future—here, becoming a firefighter.</div><div><strong>bombeiro</strong> This is a Portuguese noun that means "firefighter". It’s a profession or occupation.</div><div><strong>quando</strong> This is an adverb in Portuguese that means "when". It introduces a time clause that specifies the condition under which the action of the main verb will take place.</div><div><strong>crescer</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "crescer" in Portuguese, meaning "to grow up". It indicates the change or process of growth that will lead to the subject becoming a firefighter in the future.</div>','<h2>Vocês chorarão quando a Maria chegar.</h2><div><strong>Vocês</strong> This is the second-person plural pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English when addressing more than one person. It is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>chorarão</strong> This is the future tense of the verb "chorar", which means "to cry" in English. It indicates an action that will take place in the future, performed by the subject "vocês".</div><div><strong>quando</strong> This is a conjunction in Portuguese that translates to "when" in English. It introduces a time clause, indicating the moment when the action will occur.</div><div><strong>a Maria</strong> This is a proper noun, referring to a person named Maria. In Portuguese, it is common to use the definite article "a" before proper names.</div><div><strong>chegar</strong> This is the verb "chegar" in the subjunctive mood, present tense, which means "to arrive" in English. It is used here to express an action that is anticipated or conjectured to occur at the moment stated by the conjunction "quando".</div>','<h2>Dirigíamos quando o motor parou.</h2><div><strong>Dirigíamos</strong> Este é o pretérito imperfeito do indicativo do verbo "dirigir" na primeira pessoa do plural em português, equivalente a "we were driving" em inglês. Indica uma ação que estava ocorrendo no passado.</div><div><strong>quando</strong> Esta é a conjunção subordinativa adverbial temporal em português, equivalente a "when" em inglês. É usada para introduzir uma cláusula que especifica o tempo em que a ação principal estava ocorrendo.</div><div><strong>o</strong> Este é o artigo definido masculino singular em português, equivalente a "the" em inglês.</div><div><strong>motor</strong> Esta é uma palavra em português que significa "engine" em inglês. Refere-se à parte de uma máquina que gera força motriz.</div><div><strong>parou</strong> Este é o pretérito perfeito do indicativo do verbo "parar" na terceira pessoa do singular em português, equivalente a "stopped" em inglês. Indica uma ação completa ou um evento que ocorreu no passado.</div>','<h2>Tu estás sempre feliz quando acordas.</h2><div><strong>Tu</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It is the subject of the sentence, used in informal contexts.</div><div><strong>estás</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the verb "estar", which means "to be" in a temporary state or location. It indicates the subject’s current condition.</div><div><strong>sempre</strong> This translates to "always" in English. It is an adverb describing the frequency of the subject’s happiness.</div><div><strong>feliz</strong> This is a Portuguese adjective meaning "happy". It describes the subject’s emotional state.</div><div><strong>quando</strong> This word means "when" in English. It introduces a subordinate clause indicating the time when the subject is happy.</div><div><strong>acordas</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the verb "acordar", which means "to wake up". It describes the action that accompanies the subject’s happiness.</div>','<h2>Ela sorriu quando lhe mostrei a foto.</h2><div><strong>Ela</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in Portuguese equivalent to "she" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>sorriu</strong> This is the third-person singular past tense form of the verb "sorrir", which means "to smile". It indicates the action she performed.</div><div><strong>quando</strong> This is a conjunction in Portuguese that means "when". It introduces a time clause related to the main action.</div><div><strong>lhe</strong> This is an indirect object pronoun in Portuguese equivalent to "to him/her" or "to you(formal)" in English. It indicates to whom the action of showing was directed.</div><div><strong>mostrei</strong> This is the first-person singular past tense form of the verb "mostrar", which means "to show". It conveys the action performed by the speaker.</div><div><strong>a foto</strong> This phrase is made up of the article "a" which means "the", and the noun "foto", which means "photo" in English. It serves as the direct object of the sentence, indicating what was shown.</div>','<h2>Fiquei animado quando vi meus presentes.</h2><div><strong>Fiquei</strong> This is the first-person singular of the past tense of the verb "ficar" in Portuguese, which can translate to "become" or "got" in English. In this sentence, it means "I became" or "I got".</div><div><strong>animado</strong> This is a Portuguese adjective meaning "excited" or "enthusiastic". It’s agreeing in gender and number with the first-person singular subject implied by the verb "fiquei".</div><div><strong>quando</strong> This is a conjunction in Portuguese that means "when". It’s used to introduce a time clause that indicates the moment something happened.</div><div><strong>vi</strong> This is the first-person singular of the past tense of the verb "ver" in Portuguese, meaning "to see". It translates to "I saw" in English.</div><div><strong>meus</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in Portuguese, meaning "my". It is in the masculine plural form to match the gender and number of the noun "presentes".</div><div><strong>presentes</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "gifts" or "presents". It’s in the plural form since the speaker is indicating that there were multiple gifts.</div>','<h2>Eles pedem ajuda quando não entendem.</h2><div><strong>Eles</strong> This is the third-person plural pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "they" in English. It is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>pedem</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense form of the verb "pedir", which means "to ask" or "to request". They are requesting or asking for something in this context.</div><div><strong>ajuda</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "help" or "assistance". It is the direct object of the sentence, being the thing that "they" request.</div><div><strong>quando</strong> This is a Portuguese conjunction meaning "when". It introduces a dependent clause that specifies the conditions under which the help is requested.</div><div><strong>não</strong> This is the Portuguese adverb meaning "not". It negates the verb that follows.</div><div><strong>entendem</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense form of the verb "entender", which means "to understand". Combined with "não", it indicates that the subject does not understand something.</div>','<h2>Experimente se vestir bem quando estiver em um voo.</h2><div><strong>Experimente</strong> This is the imperative form of the verb "experimentar", which means "to try" or "to experiment" in English. It’s suggesting or advising someone to try something.</div><div><strong>se</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun that is part of a reflexive verb construction in Portuguese. It refers back to the subject of the sentence and means "yourself" in this context.</div><div><strong>vestir</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "vestir", which means "to dress" in English. It is used here in combination with "se" to form a reflexive verb meaning "to dress oneself".</div><div><strong>bem</strong> This is an adverb meaning "well" in English. It is modifying the verb "vestir", indicating the manner in which the action should be performed.</div><div><strong>quando</strong> This is a conjunction meaning "when" in English. It introduces a subordinate clause indicating the time at which the action should be performed.</div><div><strong>estiver</strong> This is the future subjunctive form of the verb "estar", which means "to be" in English. It is used here to express an action that may or may not happen in the future, conditional upon another action.</div><div><strong>em</strong> This is a preposition meaning "in" in English. It indicates the location or the setting of the action.</div><div><strong>um</strong> This is an indefinite article meaning "a" or "an" in English. It introduces the noun that follows, which is "voo".</div><div><strong>voo</strong> This is a masculine noun meaning "flight" in English. It refers to the context in which the subject is advised to try dressing well.</div>','<h2>Ela acordará quando o despertador tocar.</h2><div><strong>Ela</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "she" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>acordará</strong> This is the third-person singular future tense form of the verb "acordar", which means "to wake up". It indicates an action that will occur in the future.</div><div><strong>quando</strong> This is a Portuguese conjunction that means "when". It introduces a time clause mentioning the occasion or condition for the action.</div><div><strong>o</strong> This is the definite article "the" in English, used here in the masculine singular form because "despertador" is a masculine noun.</div><div><strong>despertador</strong> This is a noun in Portuguese meaning "alarm clock". It is the subject of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>tocar</strong> This is an infinitive form of the verb "tocar", which can mean "to play" in the sense of playing an instrument, but in this context means "to ring". It refers to the action the alarm clock will perform. </div>','<h2>O piso fica escorregadio quando está molhado.</h2><div><strong>O</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese for masculine singular nouns, similar to "the" in English.</div><div><strong>piso</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "floor" or "pavement".</div><div><strong>fica</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "ficar", which means "to become" or "to get". In this context, it indicates the state the floor gets into under certain conditions.</div><div><strong>escorregadio</strong> This is a Portuguese adjective meaning "slippery".</div><div><strong>quando</strong> This is a conjunction in Portuguese, which means "when". It introduces a dependent time clause.</div><div><strong>está</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "estar", which means "to be". It is used here to describe the current state of being.</div><div><strong>molhado</strong> This is a Portuguese past participle often used as an adjective meaning "wet". It agrees in gender and number with the masculine singular noun it describes.</div>','<h2>Ela aprende melhor quando estuda ao ar livre.</h2><div><strong>Ela</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "she" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>aprende</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "aprender", which means "to learn" in English. It indicates an action performed by the subject.</div><div><strong>melhor</strong> This is an adverb in Portuguese meaning "better". Here, it modifies the verb "aprende" indicating that the learning process is more effective.</div><div><strong>quando</strong> This is a conjunction in Portuguese that means "when". It introduces a time clause that gives additional information about the circumstances under which the subject learns better.</div><div><strong>estuda</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "estudar", which means "to study" in English. It is used in the subordinate clause to describe what the subject does.</div><div><strong>ao ar livre</strong> This is a Portuguese expression meaning "outdoors" or "in the open air". It describes the location in which the studying and learning take place.</div>','<h2>Ela ficou nervosa quando lhe contei a notícia.</h2><div><strong>Ela</strong> This is the Portuguese third-person singular pronoun which means "she". It is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>ficou</strong> This is the third-person singular past tense form of the verb "ficar", which means "to become" or "to get". In this sentence, it indicates that she became or felt a certain way.</div><div><strong>nervosa</strong> This is a Portuguese adjective meaning "nervous". The feminine singular form agrees with the feminine subject "ela". It describes her state of being as a result of the news.</div><div><strong>quando</strong> This word translates to "when" in English. It introduces a subordinate clause indicating the time at which the previously mentioned action occurred.</div><div><strong>lhe</strong> This is an indirect object pronoun meaning "him/her/you (formal)" in English. In this sentence, it is used to indicate to whom the news was told, which is the person symbolized by "ela".</div><div><strong>contei</strong> This is the first-person singular past tense form of the verb "contar", which means "to tell". Here, it denotes the action performed by the speaker in the past.</div><div><strong>a notícia</strong> This phrase means "the news" in English. It is made up of the definite article "a" (the) and the noun "notícia" (news), and is the direct object of the action of telling.</div>','<h2>Você rirá quando deixar de ser tão sério.</h2><div><strong>Você</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It is used here as the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>rirá</strong> This is a future tense conjugation of the verb "rir", meaning "to laugh". It suggests that the action will take place in the future.</div><div><strong>quando</strong> This is a conjunction in Portuguese that means "when". It introduces a time clause that states the condition under which the main action (rirá) will occur.</div><div><strong>deixar</strong> This is a verb in the infinitive form which means "to stop" or "to leave". In this context, it is part of the clause "quando deixar" which translates to "when (you) stop".</div><div><strong>de ser</strong> The preposition "de" combined with the infinitive "ser" means "of being" or "to be". The phrase "deixar de ser" is a common Portuguese construction that means "to stop being".</div><div><strong>tão</strong> This is an adverb meaning "so" or "as" in English. It is used to intensify the adjective that follows.</div><div><strong>sério</strong> This is an adjective that means "serious" in English. It describes the quality or state of the subject, "você" in this case.</div>','<h2>Sim, eu cheguei no aeroporto quando o avião decolou.</h2><div><strong>Sim</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "yes". It acknowledges a statement or responds affirmatively to a question.</div><div><strong>eu</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>cheguei</strong> This is the first-person singular past tense form of the verb "chegar", which means "to arrive". It indicates that the subject arrived at a place at a past time.</div><div><strong>no</strong> This is a contraction of the Portuguese preposition "em" (in) with the masculine article "o" (the), forming "no" which translates to "at the" in English.</div><div><strong>aeroporto</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "airport". It’s the place where aircrafts take off and land.</div><div><strong>quando</strong> This is a Portuguese conjunction meaning "when". It connects two clauses by indicating the time at which an event occurred.</div><div><strong>o</strong> This is the masculine definite article in Portuguese, equivalent to "the" in English.</div><div><strong>avião</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "airplane". It’s a vehicle designed for air travel.</div><div><strong>decolou</strong> This is the third-person singular past tense form of the verb "decolar", which means "to take off". It indicates that the airplane began its flight or left the ground.</div>','<h2>Eu morava em uma fazenda quando era mais jovem.</h2><div><strong>Eu</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>morava</strong> This is the first-person singular past imperfect tense form of the verb "morar", which means "to live". It is used to describe a past habitual action or a state of being in the past.</div><div><strong>em</strong> This is a preposition in Portuguese that can be translated as "in" or "on" in English. It’s used here to indicate the location where the action was taking place.</div><div><strong>uma</strong> This is an indefinite article in Portuguese, equivalent to "a" or "an" in English. It’s used here to modify the noun "fazenda" and means one in a non-specific way.</div><div><strong>fazenda</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "farm". It is a noun representing the place where the subject used to live.</div><div><strong>quando</strong> This is a conjunction in Portuguese meaning "when". It introduces a time clause that indicates the timing of the main action.</div><div><strong>era</strong> This is the first-person singular past imperfect tense form of the verb "ser", which means "to be". It describes a state of being or identity of the subject in the past.</div><div><strong>mais jovem</strong> This is a Portuguese phrase meaning "younger". "Mais" translates to "more", and "jovem" means "young". Combined, they describe the age of the subject at the time of the action.</div>','<h2>Você sabe me dizer quando os freios começaram a falhar?</h2><div><strong>Você</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It is used here as the subject of the question.</div><div><strong>sabe</strong> This is the third-person singular of the present indicative tense of the verb "saber", which means "to know". Here, it suggests the ability or possession of knowledge about something.</div><div><strong>me dizer</strong> This is a verbal phrase consisting of the pronoun "me", which means "me" in English, and "dizer", which is the infinitive form of the verb meaning "to tell" or "to say". Combined, "me dizer" translates to "tell me" in English.</div><div><strong>quando</strong> This is an adverb of time meaning "when" in English. It introduces the question about the time of an event.</div><div><strong>os freios</strong> This is a noun phrase where "os" is the definite article "the" in English, plural masculine form, and "freios" means "brakes". So "os freios" translates to "the brakes".</div><div><strong>começaram</strong> This is the third-person plural past tense of the verb "começar", which means "to begin" or "to start". It indicates that the action happened in the past.</div><div><strong>a falhar</strong> This is a verbal phrase consisting of the preposition "a" followed by the verb "falhar", which means "to fail" in its infinitive form. In this context, "a falhar" translates to "began to fail". </div>','<h2>Você entendia tudo quando era jovem.</h2><div><strong>Você</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It is used to address the person being spoken to directly.</div><div><strong>entendia</strong> This is the second-person singular imperfect past tense form of the verb "entender", which means "to understand". It indicates a continuous action or a habitual state in the past.</div><div><strong>tudo</strong> This is a Portuguese adverb meaning "everything". It refers to all things or the whole of what was being understood.</div><div><strong>quando</strong> This is a Portuguese conjunction or adverb that means "when". It introduces a temporal clause, connecting the time aspect of understanding to the subject’s youth.</div><div><strong>era</strong> This is the first-person and third-person singular imperfect past tense form of the verb "ser", which means "to be" in Portuguese. Here, it is used as the third-person singular referring to "você" (you) in the past, signifying the state of being young.</div><div><strong>jovem</strong> This is a Portuguese adjective meaning "young". It describes the state or characteristic of the person being addressed at the referenced time in the past.</div>','<h2>Irei para casa quando eu terminar de colher flores.</h2><div><strong>Irei</strong> This is the first-person singular future indicative tense of the Portuguese verb "ir", which means "to go". It indicates an action that will take place in the future.</div><div><strong>para</strong> This is a preposition in Portuguese that means "to" or "towards". It is often used to indicate direction or destination.</div><div><strong>casa</strong> It’s a feminine noun in Portuguese meaning "home" or "house". Here, it refers to the speaker’s destination.</div><div><strong>quando</strong> This is a conjunction in Portuguese meaning "when". It introduces a time clause that specifies the conditions under which the action of the main verb will occur.</div><div><strong>eu</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the clause that follows.</div><div><strong>terminar</strong> This is the first-person singular future subjunctive tense of the Portuguese verb "terminar", which means "to finish". It indicates an action that has not yet been completed at the time referred to.</div><div><strong>de colher</strong> The word "de" functions as a preposition here, linking the verb "terminar" with the verb "colher". "Colher" is the infinitive form meaning "to gather" or "to pick", specifically in the context of picking flowers or fruits.</div><div><strong>flores</strong> It’s a feminine noun in Portuguese meaning "flowers". Here, it is the object of the action "colher" (to pick).</div>','<h2>Quase chorei de alegria quando o avião chegou.</h2><div><strong>Quase</strong> This is a Portuguese adverb meaning "almost". It indicates that an action did not completely happen but was very close to happening.</div><div><strong>chorei</strong> This is the first-person singular past tense form of the verb "chorar", which means "to cry". It indicates that the speaker experienced the action in the past.</div><div><strong>de</strong> This is a Portuguese preposition that can have several meanings, including "of", "from", or "by". In this context, it is part of the expression "de alegria", which translates to "with joy" or "from happiness".</div><div><strong>alegria</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "happiness" or "joy". It is the object of the preposition "de" in the expression "de alegria".</div><div><strong>quando</strong> This is a conjunction in Portuguese meaning "when". It introduces a subordinate clause indicating the time at which the main action occurred.</div><div><strong>o</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese, equivalent to "the" in English. It is in the masculine singular form, matching the noun it precedes.</div><div><strong>avião</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "airplane". It is the subject of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>chegou</strong> This is the third-person singular past tense form of the verb "chegar", which means "to arrive". It tells when the speaker almost cried, marking the arrival of the airplane.</div>','<h2>Eu acredito que trabalharemos bem juntos.</h2><div><strong>Eu</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>acredito</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "acreditar", which means "to believe". Here, it signals the speaker’s conviction or opinion.</div><div><strong>que</strong> This is a conjunction in Portuguese that introduces a subordinate clause. It translates to "that" in English.</div><div><strong>trabalharemos</strong> This is the first-person plural future tense form of the verb "trabalhar", which means "to work". It indicates an action that will happen in the future, implying a joint effort.</div><div><strong>bem</strong> This is an adverb in Portuguese that means "well". It modifies the verb "trabalharemos", suggesting that the work will be done efficiently or satisfactorily.</div><div><strong>juntos</strong> This is an adverb in Portuguese that means "together". It complements "trabalharemos", indicating that the action of working will be done in collaboration.</div>','<h2>Acho que você vai gostar do seu presente.</h2><div><strong>Acho</strong> This is the first-person singular of the verb "achar" in the present indicative tense. It translates to "I think" or "I find" in English. It expresses the speaker’s opinion or belief.</div><div><strong>que</strong> This word functions as a conjunction, connecting the phrases "Acho" and "você vai gostar do seu presente". It translates to "that" in English, introducing a subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>você</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It refers to the person being spoken to.</div><div><strong>vai</strong> This is the third-person singular of the verb "ir" in the present indicative tense. Here, it creates the future tense construction "vai gostar" (will like), when combined with the infinitive "gostar". It translates to "will" or "is going to" in English.</div><div><strong>gostar</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "gostar", which means "to like" in English. It is used after "vai" to express a future action, hence "vai gostar" means "you will like".</div><div><strong>do</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "de" (of/from) with the definite article "o" (the), translating to "of the" or "from the" in English. It is used here to show possession or association with the present.</div><div><strong>seu</strong> This is a possessive pronoun that means "your" in English. It indicates ownership or relation to the person being spoken to (você).</div><div><strong>presente</strong> This is a noun meaning "present" or "gift" in English. It is the object of the sentence, referring to what the speaker thinks the listener will like.</div>','<h2>Sugiro que nós saiamos bem cedo amanhã.</h2><div><strong>Sugiro</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "sugerir", which means "to suggest" in English. The speaker is making a suggestion.</div><div><strong>que</strong> This word serves as a conjunction in the sentence, equivalent to "that" in English, introducing the clause which contains the suggestion.</div><div><strong>nós</strong> This is the first-person plural pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "we" in English. It’s the subject of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>saíamos</strong> This is the first-person plural subjunctive imperfect tense form of the verb "sair", which means "to leave" or "to go out" in English. This mood is used to express something that is uncertain or tentative.</div><div><strong>bem</strong> This is an adverb in Portuguese meaning "well" in English, but in this context, it serves as an intensifier, enhancing the meaning of the word that follows.</div><div><strong>cedo</strong> This is an adverb meaning "early" in English. Together with "bem", it’s an expression that means "very early".</div><div><strong>amanhã</strong> This is an adverb meaning "tomorrow" in English. It indicates when the action of leaving early is suggested to happen.</div>','<h2>Eu acredito que eles julguem outras pessoas.</h2><div><strong>Eu</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>acredito</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "acreditar", which means "to believe". It indicates the action performed by the subject, which in this context, is the speaker believing in something.</div><div><strong>que</strong> This word functions as a conjunction in this sentence, equivalent to "that" in English. It introduces a dependent clause.</div><div><strong>eles</strong> This is the third-person plural pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "they" in English. It’s the subject of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>julguem</strong> This is the third-person plural present subjunctive tense form of the verb "julgar", which means "to judge". In this context, it is used to express a hypothetical or non-factual action that is being believed by the speaker.</div><div><strong>outras</strong> This is the feminine plural form of the Portuguese word for "other", serving as an adjective in this sentence to modify "pessoas".</div><div><strong>pessoas</strong> This is the feminine plural noun meaning "people", serving as the direct object in the subordinate clause — they are the ones being judged, according to the speaker’s belief.</div>','<h2>Não fale com pessoas que você não conhece.</h2><div><strong>Não</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "no" or "don’t". In this sentence, it is used to give a negative imperative command, meaning "do not".</div><div><strong>fale</strong> This is the imperative form of the verb "falar", which means "to speak". The imperative is used to give orders or commands, and here it is in the second-person singular form.</div><div><strong>com</strong> This is the Portuguese preposition for "with", indicating the association between speaking and the people referred to in the sentence.</div><div><strong>pessoas</strong> This is a noun meaning "people" or "persons". It’s the object of the preposition "com" and indicates who the subject should not speak with.</div><div><strong>que</strong> This is a relative pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "that", "who", or "which" in English. It’s used to introduce the relative clause "que você não conhece" (that you do not know).</div><div><strong>você</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Brazilian Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. In the sentence, it’s the subject of the relative clause.</div><div><strong>não</strong> Again, this is the word for "no" or "not", used here to negate the verb "conhece" in the relative clause.</div><div><strong>conhece</strong> This is the third-person singular present indicative form of "conhecer", which means "to know" or "to be acquainted with". In the sentence, it’s negated by "não", forming "não conhece", which means "do not know".</div>','<h2>Sonhei que estavam caindo livros do céu.</h2><div><strong>Sonhei</strong> This is the first-person singular past tense form of the Portuguese verb "sonhar", which means "to dream". Here, it indicates that the speaker had a dream.</div><div><strong>que</strong> This word is a conjunction in Portuguese, equivalent to "that" in English. It’s used to introduce a subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>estavam</strong> This is the third-person plural form of the imperfect tense of the verb "estar", which means "to be" in a temporary state. Here, it suggests that something was happening.</div><div><strong>caindo</strong> This is the gerund form of the verb "cair", which means "to fall". It denotes ongoing action or a process in progress.</div><div><strong>livros</strong> This is the plural form of the noun "livro", which means "books" in English. It’s the subject of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>do</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "de" (from) and the definite article "o" (the), equating to "from the" or "of the" in English.</div><div><strong>céu</strong> This is a noun meaning "sky" in English. When combined with "do", it refers to the origin of where the books are falling from.</div>','<h2>É bom que limpemos a casa todos os dias.</h2><div><strong>É</strong> This is the third-person singular of the verb "ser" in the present indicative, which means "it is" or "is" in English. It’s the main verb of the sentence.</div><div><strong>bom</strong> This is a Portuguese adjective meaning "good". In the sentence, it qualifies the action of cleaning the house as a positive one.</div><div><strong>que</strong> This is a conjunction which introduces a subordinate clause, here it means "that".</div><div><strong>limpemos</strong> This is the first-person plural of the verb "limpar" in the present subjunctive, which means "we clean". It’s used to express an action that is desired or suggested, such as in this sentence where it is implied it would be good to perform the action.</div><div><strong>a casa</strong> This phrase means "the house" in English, with "a" being the definite feminine article "the", and "casa" being the feminine noun "house".</div><div><strong>todos os dias</strong> This phrase means "every day" in English, with "todos" meaning "every", "os" being the plural masculine article "the", and "dias" being the plural of "dia", which means "day".</div>','<h2>Ele grita toda vez que seu time marca um ponto.</h2><div><strong>Ele</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "he" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>grita</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "gritar", which means "to scream" or "to shout". It describes the action the subject (Ele) takes.</div><div><strong>toda vez que</strong> This phrase translates to "every time that" in English. It’s a temporal conjunction used to connect the action of screaming to the specific repeated circumstance that causes it.</div><div><strong>seu time</strong> "Seu" is a possessive pronoun that can mean "his", "her", "its", or "your" (formal) in English, and "time" means "team". So "seu time" means "his team", "her team", or "your team" depending on the context. In this case, it’s likely "his team" due to the subject "Ele".</div><div><strong>marca</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "marcar", which can mean "to score" or "to mark". In the context of this sentence, it means "scores".</div><div><strong>um ponto</strong> This phrase translates to "a point" in English. It’s the direct object of the verb "marca", indicating what is being scored by the team.</div>','<h2>Eles recomendam que nós esperemos mais um pouco.</h2><div><strong>Eles</strong> This is the third-person plural pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "they" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>recomendam</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense form of the verb "recomendar", which means "to recommend". It indicates what "they" are doing in this sentence.</div><div><strong>que</strong> This is a conjunction in Portuguese, here it introduces a subordinate clause, equivalent to "that" in English.</div><div><strong>nós</strong> This is the first-person plural pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "we" in English. It’s the subject of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>esperemos</strong> This is the first-person plural present subjunctive tense of the verb "esperar", which means "to wait". The subjunctive mood is used because there’s an expression of desire, wish or hope (recommended by someone else).</div><div><strong>mais</strong> This is an adverb in Portuguese that translates to "more" in English. It’s used to amplify the action of waiting.</div><div><strong>um pouco</strong> This phrase translates to "a little bit" in English, and it further quantifies the extent of waiting suggested.</div>','<h2>Ele insiste que investiguemos mais um pouco.</h2><div><strong>Ele</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "he" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>insiste</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "insistir", which means "to insist". It shows the action the subject is taking, emphasizing the continuance of the action.</div><div><strong>que</strong> This is a conjunction in Portuguese that introduces a subordinate clause. In this case, it is linking the main clause to the dependent clause that expresses what the subject insists on.</div><div><strong>investiguemos</strong> This is the first-person plural present subjunctive form of the verb "investigar", which means "to investigate". The use of the subjunctive mood indicates a wish, desire, or suggestion.</div><div><strong>mais</strong> This is an adverb meaning "more" in English, indicating an increase in the extent or degree of the action.</div><div><strong>um pouco</strong> This phrase combines the indefinite article "um" (a, an) with the noun "pouco" (little, bit), together meaning "a bit" or "a little". It modifies the extent to which the subject wishes to continue investigating.</div>','<h2>Ela gosta que vocês a incluam em seu grupo.</h2><div><strong>Ela</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "she" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>gosta</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "gostar", which means "to like" or "to enjoy". It indicates what the subject, "Ela", does.</div><div><strong>que</strong> This is a conjunction in Portuguese that connects the main clause "Ela gosta" with the subordinate clause "vocês a incluam em seu grupo". It can be translated to "that" in English.</div><div><strong>vocês</strong> This is the second-person plural pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" (plural) in English. It’s the subject of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>a</strong> This is the third-person singular feminine object pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "her" in English. It’s used here to refer to the subject of the main sentence, "Ela", being affected by the action.</div><div><strong>incluam</strong> This is the third-person plural present subjunctive form of the verb "incluir", which means "to include". The subjunctive mood is used because the action is something desired or hypothetical, not a guaranteed fact.</div><div><strong>em</strong> This is a preposition in Portuguese that can mean "in" or "on" in English, depending on the context. Here, it indicates inclusion within a group.</div><div><strong>seu</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in Portuguese that can mean "his", "her", "its", or "your" (formal singular) depending on the context. It shows ownership and in this sentence, it matches the subject "vocês" and refers to "your" (plural).</div><div><strong>grupo</strong> This is a masculine singular noun in Portuguese that translates to "group" in English. It serves as the object of the preposition "em" indicating the entity in which the subject is to be included.</div>','<h2>É a primeira vez que elas brincam de amarelinha.</h2><div><strong>É</strong> This is the third-person singular of the verb "ser" in Portuguese, which means "to be". It is used here to form a present tense statement.</div><div><strong>a</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese for feminine singular nouns, equivalent to "the" in English.</div><div><strong>primeira</strong> This is a feminine singular form of the ordinal number in Portuguese, meaning "first". It agrees in gender and number with the noun it modifies.</div><div><strong>vez</strong> This is a feminine singular noun in Portuguese, meaning "time" or "occasion". In this sentence, it is part of the phrase "primeira vez", which means "first time".</div><div><strong>que</strong> This is a relative pronoun in Portuguese, which can be translated to "that" in English. It introduces the subordinate clause in the sentence.</div><div><strong>elas</strong> This is the third-person plural feminine pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "they" in English when referring to a group of females or a group of people where the gender is not specified but is assumed to be female.</div><div><strong>brincam</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense form of the verb "brincar" in Portuguese, which means "to play".</div><div><strong>de</strong> This preposition in Portuguese can mean various things depending on the context, similar to "of" or "from" in English. In this case, it is part of the expression "brincar de", which means "to play" as in playing a game.</div><div><strong>amarelinha</strong> This is a noun in Portuguese, referring to the game known as "hopscotch" in English. The word literally translates to "little yellow", but in this context, it’s a children’s game.</div>','<h2>Sim, que dia lindo!</h2><div><strong>Sim</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "yes". It affirms a statement or responds affirmatively to a question.</div><div><strong>que</strong> This is a conjunction in Portuguese, which translates to "that" in English in other contexts, but in this case, it’s an exclamation meaning "what". It’s used to express emotion, surprise, or admiration, similar to "how" in the phrase "How beautiful!"</div><div><strong>dia</strong> This is a masculine noun in Portuguese meaning "day". It refers to the period of 24 hours from midnight to midnight or the daytime as opposed to the nighttime.</div><div><strong>lindo</strong> This is an adjective in Portuguese meaning "beautiful" or "lovely". It is used here to describe the day. The adjective agrees in gender and number with the noun it modifies, so if referring to a feminine noun, it would change to "linda".</div>'];definitions = definitions.concat(defBonus);